<span class="c11">&nbsp; </span><span class="c15">(VFX)</span><span class="c11 c21"><br></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c8">I&rsquo;ve been working on a better portfolio showcase with my brother and a few friends at</span><span class="c8"><a class="c3" href="https://rathouse.ca/">&nbsp;</a></span><span class="c8 c18 c24"><a class="c3" href="https://rathouse.ca/">rathouse.ca</a></span><span class="c8">&nbsp;,but since that&rsquo;s still in early development I am using these GitHub pages &nbsp;to show my work for now.</span>

<span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 549.50px; height: 307.99px;">
    
<img alt="" src="imagesW/image2.gif" style="width: 549.50px; height: 307.99px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p>

<p class="c13"><span class="c8">Above is an early version of an effect I made in Houdini (rendered in blender) that I plan to integrate into the website as a headline visual. Here is a quick overview of my workflow: </span></p><ol class="c23 lst-kix_kelsfl3kemx0-0 start" start="1"><li class="c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">&nbsp;ZBrush</span><span class="c8"><br>I sculpted a quick and dirty rat model in ZBrush. No real detail was needed, it just needed to be reminiscent of a rat&rsquo;s form.<br> </span></li><li class="c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">&nbsp;Houdini</span><span class="c8"><br></span><span class="c4">In Houdini I remeshed with tris and added normals to the points. Using the vector cross product of the normals with a predefined direction I added velocity to each particle; This way the particles would move according to the mesh&rsquo;s surface.<br><br>I then subtracted each particle&rsquo;s position by the closest proximity vector on the mesh. This pulls the particles closer to the surface of the mesh. Otherwise they would infinitely fly away due to the previously applied velocity.<br><br>I then instanced boxes onto the particles and made them each create trails of particles behind them that shrunk in size as their lifetime decreased. The colors were simply created by layering patterns of noise each with their own color.<br></span></li><li class="c2 li-bullet-0"><span class="c1">&nbsp;Blender</span><span class="c8"><br>The Houdini data was exported into 3 Alembic files: one each for the</span><span class="c14 c16">&nbsp;particle position</span><span class="c8">, </span><span class="c14 c16">orientation</span><span class="c8">, </span><span class="c14 c16">scaling</span><span class="c8">, and </span><span class="c14 c16">color attributes</span><span class="c4">. I used blender&rsquo;s geometry nodes feature to procedurally connect all this data to recreate the houdini simulation. I did this because there are many tools I am accustomed to with blender. The above render was made in Blender directly after finishing this step. I have yet to add Blender specific effects.</span></li></ol><hr><p class="c5"><span class="c4"></span></p>
